This dataset named “crimes_against_women_2001-2014.csv” contains data on various crimes committed against women in India between 2001 and 2014 at the state and district level. The crimes presented in this dataset are rape, kidnapping and abduction, dowry deaths, assault on women with intent to outrage her modesty, insult to modesty of Women, cruelty by husband or his relatives or importation of girls. This dataset is composed of 11 columns and 10 677 lines. Except for the STATE/UT and DISTRICT columns which have state/district names in their cells, the rest of the columns are columns with numeric variables (like year, number of rapes etc). Thus, we can say that these variables are quantitative variables because they are expressed by numbers.

The evolution of crimes against women in India has continued to increase over the years. We can see that the number of recorded crimes has increased from less than 300,000 in 2001 to more than 600,000. We can also observe that from 2001 to 2003, the number of crimes remained quite stable and it is only from 2006 onwards that the 300K mark of violence against women is recorded and thereafter only increases almost exponentially. With the table visible above, we notice that the more we advance in the years the more the number of victims recorded do not cease increasing. The last 5 years are the years with the most victims in India going from 409 946 victims in 2010 to 634 696 victims in 2014.

a) Hypothesis n°1

The poorest states are the one facing the more family cruelty

poor <- c("bihar", "jharkhand","uttar pradesh")
t.test(data$FamilyCruelty[data$State== "bihar"], data$FamilyCruelty[data$State== "jharkhand"])
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  data$FamilyCruelty[data$State == "bihar"] and data$FamilyCruelty[data$State == "jharkhand"]
## t = 2.445, df = 957.54, p-value = 0.01467
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   8.894234 81.241167
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
## 110.39557  65.32787

By testing this hypothesis, we found that the p-value is equal to 0.01467. It means that the hypothesis is rejected. Indeed, as the p-value is inferior to 5%, we must reject it. We can not conclude anything about the relation between poor states and the number of cases of family cruelty.

b) Hypothesis n°2

North-Eastern states face less dowry deaths than other states

northern <- c("arunachal pradesh","assam","manipur", "meghalaya", "mizoram","nagaland","tripura")
'%!in%' <- Negate('%in%')
t.test(data$DowryDeaths[data$State%in%northern], data$DowryDeaths[data$State%!in%northern])
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  data$DowryDeaths[data$State %in% northern] and data$DowryDeaths[data$State %!in% northern]
## t = -17.008, df = 10649, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -21.66073 -17.18377
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  3.129701 22.551952

We get a p-value that is very near 0 because it is 2.2e-16,10. The mean of dowry deaths is North-eastern states is 3.13 while in other states its 22.55. We can conclude that in this part of the country, it is real that dowry deaths are less committed. It can be explained by the fact that in these states of India the system is very matriarchal, the societies are mainly tribal, and it explains the very absence of dowry by this side. But unfortunatelly, the -value does not allow any conclusion on this hypothesis.

4. Regression Analysis (Gabriel)

After some introductory analysis of our data set we can now analyse the relationships between our variables, and later on, predict what values these might take in the future. For this, we started by checking which are the correlations between some of the variables, and establish linear regressions in order to see how changes in some of them impact the values of others. We established relationships between the number of Rapes and two other Variables, Insults and Kidnapping Abductions. With these, our goal is to observe if, and how much Insults and Kidnapping Abductions contribute to the increase of Rapes in India. The other relationships we established were between Dowry Deaths and two other variables, Family Cruelty and Assaults Outrage. It might be obvious that an increase in Assaults Outrage and Family Cruelty will result in a higher number of Dowry Deaths, but our goal will be to confirm this and check at which extent it might happen. Finally our regressions were made considering the two regions with higher criminality rates, Uttar Pradesh and Andhra Pradesh.

data_nr <- data1 %>%
  filter(!(District %in% 'TOTAL'))

In Uttar Pradesh, the correlation between rapes and insults is extremely close to zero, which indicates that Insults towards women are not related with the number of Rapes. The same occurs with insults and kidnapping abductions. These shows us that the number of insults probably do not affect the number of rapes and kidnapping abductions. On the other hand, the relationship between kidnapping abductions and rapes is extremely positive. This means that, if both occur, they will vary perfectly in the same direction.

y_rape_uttar <- data_nr[data_nr$State=='uttar pradesh',]$Rape
x1_uttar <- data_nr[data_nr$State=='uttar pradesh',]$Insult
x2_uttar <- data_nr[data_nr$State=='uttar pradesh',]$Kidnapping_Abduction

5. Forecasting (Cécile & Yingxue)

In India, dowry deaths are still a major point of concerns. From this lollipop chart, it appears clearly that most of dowry deaths occur in Uttar Pradesh. As anti-dowry movement are developing within India and awareness is growing on that matter, we thought it would be interesting to predict the future amount of dowry deaths in this state.

TotalDowryDeaths <- sum(data_nr$DowryDeaths)
TopIndia <- data_nr %>%
  group_by(State) %>%
  summarize(DowryDeaths = sum(DowryDeaths),) %>%
  top_n(10) %>%
  arrange(desc(DowryDeaths))
## Selecting by DowryDeaths
ggplot(TopIndia, aes(x = State, y = DowryDeaths)) +
  geom_segment(aes(xend = State, yend = 0)) +
  geom_point(size = 4, color = "orange") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_bw() +
  xlab("")+
  ggtitle("Top 10 of States with highest Dowry Deaths in India")

To do so, we will conduct different time series forecasting analyses (such as EWMA, ARMA…) based on the data we already have and that have been collected annually between 2001 and 2014. This will help us to answer some questions such as: what is the trend of this kind of crime? What will be situation in the next 12 years? The following parts will help us to understand better this point and to answer our questions.

a) Plot analysis & trend extraction

We can consider the time series of dowry deaths that have been reported in Uttar Pradesh. We can plot it across time from 2002 until 2014, using the year in the x’s and dowry deaths in the y’s.

Annual_DD_UP <- data_nr %>%  
  filter(State=="uttar pradesh") %>%
  select(c(4,7))%>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarise(DowryDeaths = sum(DowryDeaths))

plot(Annual_DD_UP$Year, Annual_DD_UP$DowryDeaths, type="l", main="Number of reported Dowry Deaths per Year in Uttar Pradesh", xlab="Year", ylab= "Number of reported dowry deaths")

From our time series related to the reported dowry deaths per year in Uttar Pradesh, some patterns emerge. From 2001-2003, there is clearly a decreasing trend reaching a peak in 2003. From 2004, we can clearly identify an upward sloping trend. We can also add that this time series is non-stationary. The reason is that the correlation structure does not remain constant over time (2001-2003 vs. 2003-2014) à to check again.

b) Simple Moving Average

  • Choosing the k

K has been chosen based on minimizing the sum of squared errors,The chunk below create a Moving average of order 1

y<-rev(Annual_DD_UP$DowryDeaths)
MA<-e<-sumsqe<-c()
# for each k we calculate the sum of squared errors
for(k in 1:12){ # Note that 15 is an arbitrary number.
for(t in (k+1):length(y)){
MA[t]=mean(y[(t-k):(t-1)])
e[t]=y[t]-MA[t]
}
sumsqe[k]<-sum(e[!is.na(e)]^2)
}

k<-which.min(sumsqe)
k
## [1] 1
y<-rev(Annual_DD_UP$DowryDeaths)
MA<-c()
k<-1
MA[1:k]=mean(y[1:k])
for(t in (k+1):length(y)){
  MA[t]=mean(y[(t-k):(t-1)])
}
plot(ts(y),main="Number of reported dowry deaths with the moving average of order 1",
     ylab="Dowry Deaths",xlab="Years"); lines(MA,col="red")

c) EWMA

  • Choosing alpha
n = length(y)
ALPHA = seq(0, 1, length.out = 100)
sumsqe <- c()
for (i in 1:length(ALPHA)) {
  EWMA <- c()
  EWMA[1] <- y[1]
  alpha = ALPHA[i]
  for (t in 2:n) {
    EWMA[t] = alpha * y[t - 1] + (1 - alpha) * EWMA[t - 1]
  }
  sumsqe[i] = mean((y - EWMA) ^ 2)
}
n = length(y)
EWMA <- c()

EWMA[1] <- y[1]
alpha = ALPHA[which.min(sumsqe)]
for (t in 2:n) {
  EWMA[t] = alpha * y[t - 1] + (1 - alpha) * EWMA[t - 1]
}
plot(ts(y),
     main = "Number of reported deaths with EWMA",
     ylab = "Dowry Deaths",
     xlab = "Years"); lines(EWMA, col = "red")

d) ARMA

From our dowry death time series, we will conduct a forecasting analysis using the ARMA model. Despite this model is in principle conceived for stationary data, using it on our time series would still be interesting to understand and predict future values.

y <- rev(Annual_DD_UP$DowryDeaths)
e <- c()
e[1] = 0
sumsqerr <-
  function(param) {
    phi = param[1]
    theta = param[2]
    const = param[3]
    
    for (t in 2:length(y)) {
      e[t] <- y[t] - (const + phi * y[t - 1] + theta * e[t - 1])
    }
    mean(e ^ 2)
  }
results <- optim(c(.9, -.7, 400), sumsqerr)
phi = results[[1]][1]
theta = results[[1]][2]
const = results[[1]][3]

yhat = c()
yhat[1] = const / (1 - phi)
for (t in 2:length(y)) {
  yhat[t] <- const + phi * y[t - 1] + theta * e[t - 1]
  e[t] <- y[t] - (const + phi * y[t - 1] + theta * e[t - 1])
}
plot(ts(y),
     main = "Number of reported dowry deaths with ARMA",
     ylab = "Dowry Deaths",
     xlab = "Years")
lines(yhat, col = "red")

After running our code, we can now see the predictions for the 14 next years to come using the ARMA model (given by the red line). The black line is only a representation of the reverse of the results we got from 2002 to 2014.

The parameters of our model are the following ones:

print(c(const,phi,theta))
## [1] 664.6140754   0.6735693  -2.2055309

e) Pick a technique

Since we used three models to forecast, we want to know which one is the best solution for forecasting,thus we try to rank the forecasting models.

In order to assess which forecast is best, we will use the Root Mean Squared Scale Error (RMSSE).

Let’s define:
- Insample: the data used for estimating the model,
- Outsample: the data to be forecasted, - Forc: the forecast provided by a model and h the steps ahead - h: the time horizon to forecast

rmsse <- function(Outsample, Insample, Forc, h) {
  sqrt(mean((Outsample[1:h] - Forc[1:h]) ^ 2) / mean(diff(Insample) ^ 2))
}


OUT <- tail(y, 12)
IN <- head(y, length(y) - 12)


rmsse(OUT, IN, EWMA, 12)
## [1] 4.995692
rmsse(OUT, IN, yhat, 12)
## [1] 2.063468
rmsse(OUT, IN, MA, 12)
## [1] 4.995692

As our RMSSE function applied to our different predictions using the 3 different models are above 1, it means that our forecast errors squared are bigger than the means of our differences data squared.

Therefore, it looks like the Random walk will be the best predictor of the series. This model assumes that the variable takes a random step away from its previous value at each period and the steps are independently and identically distributed in size.

f) Random walk

n = length(y)
RW <- c()
RW[1] = y[n]
for (t in 2:n) {
  RW[t] = RW[t - 1]
}

plot(ts(y),
     main = "Number of reported dowry deaths with Random Walk",
     ylab = "Dowry Deaths",
     xlab = "Years"); 
lines(RW, col = "red")

rmsse(OUT, IN, RW, 12)
## [1] 1.4316

The RMSSE obtained applying the Random Walk model is still above 1. However, it is the lowest RMSSE we found so far. Thus, we can conclude that the random walk model can be considered as the best model to use to predict the future reported dowry deaths among ARMA, EWMA and SMA.
